# 🔹 What is a Tree?

A Tree is a **non-linear hierarchical data structure**.

It consists of:

* Nodes
* Edges

Example:

```text
        A
      /   \
     B     C
    / \   / \
   D   E F   G
```

---

# 🔹 Important Terminologies

### Root Node

Topmost node.

Example:

```text
A
```

is root.

---

### Parent Node

A node having children.

Example:

```text
A
```

is parent of B and C.

---

### Child Node

Node connected below parent.

---

### Leaf Node

Node with no children.

Example:

```text
D E F G
```

---

### Siblings

Nodes having same parent.

Example:

```text
B and C
```

---

### Degree of Node

Number of children.

---

### Height of Tree

Number of edges in longest root-to-leaf path.

📌 Frequently asked in GATE.

---

# 🔹 Binary Tree

A tree where each node has at most:

[
2
]

children.

Structure:

```c
struct Node
{
   int data;
   struct Node *left;
   struct Node *right;
};
```

---

# 🔹 Types of Binary Trees

---

## 1️⃣ Full Binary Tree

Every node has:

* 0 children OR
* 2 children

---

## 2️⃣ Complete Binary Tree

All levels full except possibly last.

Last level filled left to right.

📌 Used in Heaps.

---

## 3️⃣ Perfect Binary Tree

All internal nodes have 2 children.

All leaves at same level.

---

## 4️⃣ Skewed Binary Tree

Every node has only one child.

Example:

```text
1
 \
  2
   \
    3
```

Behaves like linked list.

---

# 🔹 Binary Tree Properties

For level i:

[
Maximum\ Nodes = 2^i
]

---

Maximum nodes in height h:

[
2^{h+1}-1
]

---

Minimum height for n nodes:

[
\lceil \log_2(n+1)\rceil -1
]

📌 Important numerical questions.

---

# 🔹 Tree Traversals (VERY IMPORTANT)

Traversal = visiting all nodes.

---

## 1️⃣ Preorder

Rule:

```text
Root → Left → Right
```

Example:

```text
      A
     / \
    B   C
```

Traversal:

```text
A B C
```

---

## 2️⃣ Inorder

Rule:

```text
Left → Root → Right
```

Traversal:

```text
B A C
```

---

## 3️⃣ Postorder

Rule:

```text
Left → Right → Root
```

Traversal:

```text
B C A
```

---

## 4️⃣ Level Order

Breadth-first traversal.

Uses Queue.

---

📌 Traversal questions are extremely common in GATE.

---

# 🔹 Binary Search Tree (BST)

Special Binary Tree.

Property:

[
Left < Root < Right
]

Example:

```text
        50
       /  \
     30    70
    / \   / \
   20 40 60 80
```

---

# 🔹 BST Search

Compare and move:

* Smaller → Left
* Larger → Right

Time Complexity:

[
O(h)
]

where h = height.

---

# 🔹 BST Inorder Traversal

Important Property:

👉 Inorder traversal of BST gives:

```text
Sorted Order
```

📌 One of the most asked GATE concepts.

---

# 🔹 Complexity Comparison

| Operation | BST  |
| --------- | ---- |
| Search    | O(h) |
| Insert    | O(h) |
| Delete    | O(h) |

Balanced BST:

[
O(\log n)
]

Worst Case:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

Inorder of BST is always sorted.

✅ TRUE

---

### Trap 2

Height ≠ Number of Nodes.

---

### Trap 3

Complete tree ≠ Full tree.

---

### Trap 4

Level order traversal uses Queue, not Stack.

